[1]
Date: Fri. 21 May, 1999
From: Birgit Puschner <bpuschne@cvdls.ucdavis.edu>
Source: California Department of Food and Agriculture, Release CDFA99-034

Merced County, Sacramento, California - The California Department of Food
and Agriculture (CDFA), with assistance from the California Veterinary
Diagnostic Laboratory System (CVDLS), is investigating the deaths of
approximately 100 cows at a Merced County dairy over the past 10 days.
CDFA veterinarians have conducted extensive examinations at the Hibma Dairy
in Turlock this week to determine the exact cause of the deaths. Multiple
samples taken from the dairy have undergone a battery of tests by CVDLS
toxicologists and diagnosticians. All clinical signs indicate the cows
died from exposure to botulism. Furthermore, extensive laboratory testing
has ruled out all other likely diseases and toxicants.

California State Veterinarian Dr. Richard Breitmeyer, CDFA's leading
authority on food safety, has inspected the dairy and has assigned a team
of 20 - 25 veterinarians, laboratory diagnosticians, dairy foods
specialists and livestock inspectors to continue to investigate the matter.
CDFA staff at the dairy are sifting through rain-damaged hay reportedly fed
to the animals. Presently, the hay is the most likely source of the
botulism toxin.
The CDFA has been working closely with a team of experts at the California
Department of Health Services, the United States Food and Drug
Administration and the University of California, Davis, to ensure the
public's safety. All milk products that were distributed underwent
high-heat processing into butter. State and federal officials agree that
this process eliminates any public exposure to botulism.
All samples collected from the dairy are sent to the California Veterinary
Diagnostic Laboratory System for analysis. The laboratory provides the
state with vital support service for livestock and poultry disease control
and health management. Operating under the University of California, Davis,
School of Veterinary Medicine, the lab is funded by an annual contract
between CDFA and the University.
For further information on CDFA Animal Health and Food Safety Services,
visit the Department's web site at www.cdfa.ca.gov/animal.
---
Birgit Puschner
e-mail: bpuschne@cvdls.ucdavis.edu
